This project has shed light on the importance of high school physics teachers and their practices for attracting more women to physics.  Indeed, high school may be the last time point where a large number of women can be engaged to learn and persist in physics with the help of a supportive high school teacher (Figure 1, representation of women in physics at various educational levels).

In terms of intellectual merit, the project deepened our understanding of how and why particular physics teacher practices facilitate students? physics identity development.  In other words, how teachers can help more students feel capable, interested, and recognized in physics, particularly women who suffer the greatest attitudinal setbacks in physics.  The project resulted in several publications in leading journals which:

(i) Described and tested a theory for measuring physics identity (Figure 2, physics identity framework); 
(ii) Explored how physics identity differs by gender and race/ethnicity (Figure 3, gender differences in physics identity across select race/ethnicity groups); 
(iii) Identified teachers? practices related to physics identity development, particularly for women (Figure 4, testing strategies for women); 
(iv) Investigated why these practices may be impactful (Figure 5, connecting teacher practices to students? physics identities); 
(v) Examined the longitudinal influence of teachers? practices and tested the effect of a workshop that exposed teachers to practices that facilitate students? physics identity development. 

Given these intellectual contributions, the project has significantly advanced work on disciplinary identity in physics in both theoretical and practical ways.  The practical strategies involve engaging students in learning physics in ways that allow them to feel capable even when challenged, capture their interests, and recognize their abilities in multiple ways.

The broader impact of the project included communicating the results of this research to science education researchers, teacher educators, and physics teachers to promote change in practice.  These results include the empirically-tested framework for physics identity development and, importantly, a set of practical pedagogical strategies for high school physics teachers to use in their classrooms.  The results of this work directly reached the teachers participating in the study and the hundreds of students they teach each year.  In addition, strategies that specifically help women develop physics identities were not only disseminated but also used by participating teachers.   This is important since women represent only a fifth of physics undergraduates even though they make up roughly half the overall population.  Furthermore, gender differences in physics identity are consistent across different race/ethnicity groups.  Given that attracting more women to physics is one of the most pressing concerns for broadening participation in physics, this project has led to subsequent grant proposals focused on national initiatives to recruit more women to physics which are in collaboration with the American Association of Physics Teachers and the American Physical Society. 

